00:00:43.438 --> 00:00:45.730
Before we do that, I just
want to give you a little bit

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:48.320
of background on A3 as a tool.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:50.050
So in this module,
we expect you to be

00:00:50.050 --> 00:00:52.220
able to do two
things at the end.

00:00:52.220 --> 00:00:55.780
First is to recognize
that A3 is not just a tool

00:00:55.780 --> 00:00:57.820
but really is a way
of thinking, a way

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:01.043
of trying to solve a problem
in a very structured way.

00:01:01.043 --> 00:01:03.460
And secondly, we want you to
gain a little bit of practice

00:01:03.460 --> 00:01:06.940
with using the tool of an
A3 chart as a standard tool

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:08.840
for implementing lean projects.

00:01:08.840 --> 00:01:09.340
All right.

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:11.650
So first of all,
A3 is really a tool

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:15.760
for enabling our whole
PDSA or PDCA cycle.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:19.390
And this is a snapshot
of one particular version

00:01:19.390 --> 00:01:22.210
of an A3 tool up in the corner.

00:01:22.210 --> 00:01:25.840
So as we said in the
goals for our module here,

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:30.460
A3 is not just a tool, but
it is also a way of thinking.

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:34.400
It originally evolved as a
management process from Toyota.

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.400
And it's named for the
A3 size sheet of paper,

00:01:37.400 --> 00:01:40.210
which is roughly 11 by 17.

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:45.232
And it was chosen as the form
for this particular exercise,

00:01:45.232 --> 00:01:47.440
because it is the largest
piece of paper that can fit

00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:49.660
through a fax machine in Japan.

00:01:49.660 --> 00:01:51.400
So you could contain
all the information

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:53.275
you needed on that one
page, and it was still

00:01:53.275 --> 00:01:55.302
easily translatable
to anywhere else,

00:01:55.302 --> 00:01:57.010
because you could put
it in a fax machine

00:01:57.010 --> 00:01:59.010
and someone at the other
end would get it and be

00:01:59.010 --> 00:02:01.630
able to see the whole
description of your problem

00:02:01.630 --> 00:02:03.220
and your courses
of action presented

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:04.510
on that one piece of paper.

00:02:07.850 --> 00:02:10.090
So here is in more
detail an example

00:02:10.090 --> 00:02:13.120
of an A3 sheet that was
developed at Toyota.

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.370
You can see on
your tables we have

00:02:15.370 --> 00:02:19.070
some starts of an A3 sheet
for the Rockwell Collins case

00:02:19.070 --> 00:02:19.570
study.

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:21.700
And they're also
blown up here very

00:02:21.700 --> 00:02:25.300
largely on the butcher paper
that's around the room.

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:27.430
And they're broken down
into several sections.

00:02:27.430 --> 00:02:29.980
And I just want to spend
the next couple of slides

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:32.355
walking you through the
basic purpose of an A3

00:02:32.355 --> 00:02:33.730
and the different
sections of it.

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:36.190
And I really have to
thank Susan for giving us

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:39.113
this great introduction to
A3 as a tool in her talk

00:02:39.113 --> 00:02:40.030
that happened earlier.

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:41.830
And she showed you
some excellent examples

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:45.410
of what these actually look
like when they're created.

00:02:45.410 --> 00:02:47.710
So first, at the top you
want to start with a title.

00:02:47.710 --> 00:02:49.310
What is it that
you're talking about?

00:02:49.310 --> 00:02:52.600
What is the focus of your
problem investigation?

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:54.250
Then there's some
background on why

00:02:54.250 --> 00:02:56.860
you're talking about it and
the particular business context

00:02:56.860 --> 00:02:58.780
for the problem
you're examining.

00:02:58.780 --> 00:03:00.660
Then more detail on
the current situation.

00:03:00.660 --> 00:03:02.540
And you saw in
Susan's representation

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:04.570
some great pictures
and diagrams.

00:03:04.570 --> 00:03:06.280
Pictures can be worth
a thousand words.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:08.140
They're very helpful
in communicating that.

00:03:08.140 --> 00:03:12.280
Sometimes a picture and some
couple of phrases of text

00:03:12.280 --> 00:03:14.110
may be all that you need.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:15.942
Then there's some
analysis usually done,

00:03:15.942 --> 00:03:17.650
trying to get at,
really, what's the root

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:19.750
cause of the problem
you're seeing,

00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:21.700
requirements, constraints,
or alternatives

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:22.863
that have to be considered.

00:03:22.863 --> 00:03:25.030
And then lastly down here,
although it's sliding off

00:03:25.030 --> 00:03:26.900
the page, is the goal.

00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:28.840
So what's the specific
change that you

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:31.510
want to accomplish now?

00:03:31.510 --> 00:03:34.060
So this is called the
left-hand side of the A3.

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:36.280
And then over here on
the right-hand side

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:37.870
starts up with your
recommendations.

00:03:37.870 --> 00:03:40.390
So what's your proposed
countermeasures

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:44.560
to remedy the root causes that
you've identified over here

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:46.180
and get to your goal?

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:49.240
Then a plan for how
you're going to implement

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:51.850
those recommendations, and
who's going to do what and when,

00:03:51.850 --> 00:03:52.982
and then some follow-up.

00:03:52.982 --> 00:03:54.940
So how will you know if
the actions that you're

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:58.160
planning really have the impact
that you expected they do?

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:01.630
And this not only lets you know
that your actions have been

00:04:01.630 --> 00:04:04.150
successful, but it also
confirms that your understanding

00:04:04.150 --> 00:04:05.470
of the problem was right.

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:07.990
Because of what you thought
was going to happen happened,

00:04:07.990 --> 00:04:09.520
that's a good
reinforcement for it.

00:04:12.810 --> 00:04:13.310
All right.

00:04:13.310 --> 00:04:16.519
So we just want to stress again
that the thought process used

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:19.160
in A3 thinking-- thinking
about the context,

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:21.589
analyzing the problem,
figuring out root causes,

00:04:21.589 --> 00:04:25.160
setting a goal, thinking about
your steps to then remedy it--

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:27.590
it really is a thought
process, it's not just a tool.

00:04:27.590 --> 00:04:30.600
And sometimes you hear
people talking about A3,

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:33.080
and sometimes it feels like
they get lost in the tool

00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:36.210
and they've somewhat
forgotten about the process.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:37.910
Another important
attribute of this,

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:39.890
it really is collaborative.

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:42.020
Everybody should get
around an A3 sheet.

00:04:42.020 --> 00:04:45.270
It's small enough so you
can all see what's going on,

00:04:45.270 --> 00:04:48.020
and it lets people who are
all part of the solutions

00:04:48.020 --> 00:04:51.740
get together to figure out
how to solve the problem.

00:04:51.740 --> 00:04:54.920
It promotes very logical
and objective thinking.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:57.740
We stress having
data on your A3 sheet

00:04:57.740 --> 00:05:01.490
in your description of the
situation and in the analysis.

00:05:01.490 --> 00:05:04.160
It lets you think about
the results and the process

00:05:04.160 --> 00:05:07.160
that you might take to try to
meet some of your objectives.

00:05:07.160 --> 00:05:10.340
It forces you to be synthetic
about the problem you're

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:13.440
thinking about, because you only
have one A3 page to write it

00:05:13.440 --> 00:05:13.940
on.

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.273
So you've got to be able to
understand your problem well

00:05:16.273 --> 00:05:18.920
enough, distill it well
enough, that you can convey it

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:21.850
in a nice, contained space.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:25.820
It forces alignment between
the context of the situation,

00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:28.160
the problems you're seeing,
the root causes of those,

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:29.720
the goals that you
want to achieve,

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:31.095
and the actions
that you're going

00:05:31.095 --> 00:05:32.420
to take to make that happen.

00:05:32.420 --> 00:05:33.950
Those all have to be aligned.

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:37.100
And you can see that
in the A3 sheet.

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:39.890
Then as a result, you have
some coherence, both within

00:05:39.890 --> 00:05:42.860
and consistency across all
these elements in your A3 sheet.

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:46.010
And it really makes sure that
you take a systems perspective

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:49.100
on the problem to get
out of those silos.

00:05:51.718 --> 00:05:53.260
So just a little
bit more information

00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:55.060
about each section of the A3.

00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.520
So we'll start with what's
typically on the left-hand

00:05:57.520 --> 00:05:58.240
side--

00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:02.080
the background, the current
situation, analysis, and goals.

00:06:02.080 --> 00:06:04.720
Diagrams are very
useful and efficient

00:06:04.720 --> 00:06:07.210
for communicating in
small spaces like that.

00:06:07.210 --> 00:06:11.500
And on Susan's examples of
A3, you saw a lot of diagrams.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.950
Value stream maps were shown up
in the current situation, which

00:06:14.950 --> 00:06:19.000
showed the items of interest,
the process flow between them.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.970
It showed you some data on
that, and then identified

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:26.350
those cloudbursts of areas
where there were problems.

00:06:26.350 --> 00:06:29.550
So some useful questions to ask
as you start to put together

00:06:29.550 --> 00:06:31.350
the left side of the sheet.

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:34.860
Are the activities clearly
specified with regards

00:06:34.860 --> 00:06:37.890
to the content, in order,
and intended outcomes

00:06:37.890 --> 00:06:41.280
as you work through the current
situation analysis and goals?

00:06:41.280 --> 00:06:43.680
And are the connections
between all the entities

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:46.170
that are involved in
your A3 problem very

00:06:46.170 --> 00:06:49.410
clear and explicit?

00:06:49.410 --> 00:06:52.860
So now, moving over to the
right-hand side of the A3

00:06:52.860 --> 00:06:53.700
sheet--

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:56.168
thinking about
recommendations and plans.

00:06:56.168 --> 00:06:57.960
When you're thinking
about recommendations,

00:06:57.960 --> 00:07:00.043
you really want to make
sure that they're directly

00:07:00.043 --> 00:07:01.330
addressing the root cause.

00:07:01.330 --> 00:07:03.630
So there has to be
consistency between that part

00:07:03.630 --> 00:07:05.340
of your A3 sheet and
where you describe

00:07:05.340 --> 00:07:07.860
the root causes taking place.

00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:11.250
And they really should help
you evolve your process

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:12.930
from the current state
towards something

00:07:12.930 --> 00:07:15.600
that you see as an ideal
state by eliminating

00:07:15.600 --> 00:07:17.130
some of the root causes.

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:18.778
And then in the
plan section, that's

00:07:18.778 --> 00:07:20.820
where you're going to
define the steps to correct

00:07:20.820 --> 00:07:21.960
each of the root causes--

00:07:21.960 --> 00:07:25.140
so, again, traceability and
connectivity, back to that.

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:26.760
And in the process
of doing so, you

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:30.270
have to identify who exactly is
responsible for what, and when,

00:07:30.270 --> 00:07:34.800
and exactly what it is
that they're going to do.

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:36.710
And then the last
part of the A3 sheet

00:07:36.710 --> 00:07:38.940
is really the continuous
improvement part of it.

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:41.040
This is your
follow-up activities.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:44.600
So how do you know that what
you wanted to happen, happened?

00:07:44.600 --> 00:07:47.240
And make sure that when you're
thinking about what you're

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:49.130
going to look at in
the follow-up section,

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:52.070
that links back to your
original goals for this,

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:56.190
and the criteria and metrics
that you set up for that.

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:58.970
So we have an example
here in the module.

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:01.213
Susan has already teed up
a lot of great examples.

00:08:01.213 --> 00:08:03.630
And you're going to be going
through one in your exercise.

00:08:03.630 --> 00:08:06.050
So I don't think I
want to spend much time

00:08:06.050 --> 00:08:07.560
on this particular example.

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:11.210
This happens to be from Acme
stamping steering bracket value

00:08:11.210 --> 00:08:14.330
stream improvement exercise.

00:08:14.330 --> 00:08:17.210
And just to show you the breadth
of situations across which

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:20.120
A3 thinking can apply,
you see one here

00:08:20.120 --> 00:08:21.560
for manufacturing process.

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:24.050
We saw lots for health
care from Susan.

00:08:24.050 --> 00:08:26.810
And now we're going to go
and do one in the office area

00:08:26.810 --> 00:08:28.110
and accounts payable.

00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:31.220
So really, there's no limit
to the context in which you

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:33.049
can apply A3 thinking,
because it's really

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:36.409
all about structured
problem solving.

00:08:36.409 --> 00:08:38.600
What I will note before
leaving this example

00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:42.570
is the prevalence of the
visual types of information.

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:45.260
So they have their current
state map, a future state

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:47.630
map on here, a Gantt
chart that they

00:08:47.630 --> 00:08:49.805
have used to describe
their plan, which

00:08:49.805 --> 00:08:51.680
are all the deliverables
that have to happen,

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:54.050
and who is going to do them,
who's responsible for them,

00:08:54.050 --> 00:08:55.040
and when.

00:08:55.040 --> 00:08:57.440
So you can see how these
visual representations

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:01.430
pack a lot of information
into a nice, tight space.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:05.900
Further examples-- we
may have come across this

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:07.160
in our New Balance video.

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:08.390
I can't recall exactly.

00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:11.510
But when you go into the
New Balance plant for sure,

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.093
you see these--

00:09:13.093 --> 00:09:14.510
they're actually
whiteboard-sized,

00:09:14.510 --> 00:09:15.560
so a little bit large.

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:18.230
So you can actually have people
with markers writing on them.

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:19.640
This is an A3 chart.

00:09:19.640 --> 00:09:22.170
And it's up around
the factory floor.

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:25.880
So that's an incredibly powerful
boundary-spanning object.

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:27.590
And all the workers
in a cell can

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:29.630
get together around
their A3 board

00:09:29.630 --> 00:09:32.612
and strategize about
problem solving.

00:09:32.612 --> 00:09:34.070
And here's an
example where they've

00:09:34.070 --> 00:09:36.680
written up in this section
their root cause analysis.

00:09:36.680 --> 00:09:39.860
And they chose to do a
five whys to get down

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:41.540
to their root cause.

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:44.715
And it's just wonderful to
see this being used right

00:09:44.715 --> 00:09:45.590
on the factory floor.

00:09:45.590 --> 00:09:47.510
And it's quite
powerful to have that

00:09:47.510 --> 00:09:49.400
there right in
front of the station

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:50.950
where everybody is
doing their work.

00:09:50.950 --> 00:09:53.070
So it's not kept by somebody
else in a desk drawer

00:09:53.070 --> 00:09:53.570
somewhere.

00:09:53.570 --> 00:09:54.820
It's just up front and visual.

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:57.980
All right.

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:01.100
So now let's move into our
exercise for this module, which

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:05.390
is taking the Rockwell Collins
accounts payable case study.

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:10.730
And we're going to use that
to create an A3 sheet on what

00:10:10.730 --> 00:10:13.040
we should do to try to
