00:22:32.810 --> 00:22:34.010
oh, you've got a new system?

00:22:34.010 --> 00:22:36.032
Well, I don't like
this new system.

00:22:36.032 --> 00:22:37.240
I don't know this new system.

00:22:37.240 --> 00:22:39.160
I'm not going to
follow this new system.

00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:41.590
And they started calling all
their contacts and saying,

00:22:41.590 --> 00:22:43.450
look, you know, they've
implemented this new system,

00:22:43.450 --> 00:22:44.290
but forget about it.

00:22:44.290 --> 00:22:46.832
If you have a problem, just
give me a call directly.

00:22:46.832 --> 00:22:48.790
And they just totally
subverted all the systems

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:51.970
that were put in place, largely
because they didn't understand

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:53.920
that the document
imaging and Lotus Notes

00:22:53.920 --> 00:22:55.723
was going to be useful for them.

00:22:55.723 --> 00:22:56.890
So Rockwell said, all right.

00:22:56.890 --> 00:22:59.140
You know what, we'll just--
we'll back away from this,

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:02.640
and we'll do this sort of in
a staged deployment method.

00:23:02.640 --> 00:23:04.420
So they just got the
analysts trained up

00:23:04.420 --> 00:23:07.850
and comfortable on the document
imaging to see that was useful.

00:23:07.850 --> 00:23:09.460
And then when that
happened, then they

00:23:09.460 --> 00:23:12.130
went to their pooled
queue calling center

00:23:12.130 --> 00:23:13.430
and then initiated that.

00:23:13.430 --> 00:23:16.150
So it took a little while,
but they eventually got it.

00:23:16.150 --> 00:23:18.940
But the implementation
was challenging because

00:23:18.940 --> 00:23:22.240
of these issues that very
perceptively were raised

00:23:22.240 --> 00:23:24.910
just about, human nature
and organizational natures

00:23:24.910 --> 00:23:27.190
when we come into
big change problems.

00:23:27.190 --> 00:23:27.830
Yes.

00:23:27.830 --> 00:23:30.310
AUDIENCE: So how does the
culture of organization

00:23:30.310 --> 00:23:34.000
play a role in implementation
of recommendations?

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.682
ANNALISA L. WEIGEL: It
plays a huge role, right?

00:23:36.682 --> 00:23:38.140
I mean, we've kind
of been alluding

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:41.800
to this over the course
the last couple of days.

00:23:41.800 --> 00:23:44.410
And some cultures and
the way that they operate

00:23:44.410 --> 00:23:46.330
are going to be more
amenable to change--

00:23:46.330 --> 00:23:48.663
that may be part of their
culture-- and accepting of it.

00:23:48.663 --> 00:23:50.890
And others are not going
to accept change so much.

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:53.320
And you have to really
recognize which one you're in so

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:55.510
that you can approach
any kind of change effort

00:23:55.510 --> 00:23:58.540
in a way that's going to make
sense to the organization

00:23:58.540 --> 00:24:02.045
that you're in and be
productive as a result.

00:24:02.045 --> 00:24:03.670
But it's a really
big topic, and longer

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:06.010
than we have time to address
in a quick question here.

00:24:06.010 --> 00:24:08.670
But we can talk about
it during the break.